entry.title: Enable sandbox shims to work regardless of timing
entry.content:
There are several limitations with the sandbox shims, root caused as

chromium sometimes accessing the Windows heap before it is safe to do

so, when OS code attempts to call NtCreateSection or NtMapViewOfSection

during super-early process start-up.



NtCreateSection - used to bypass CIG checks for binaries not signed by

Microsoft by brokering the syscall.



NtMapViewOfSection - used to listen to DLL loads in case we want to

also shim those DLLs.



This change adds early exits to the NtMapViewOfSection when these APIs

are called before kernel32 is loaded, to avoid needing to use the heap

while the process is in this super-early startup phase. There is not a

great publicly documented API we can use earlier, as Windows public API

is generally in kernel32, ntdll is mostly undocumented.



It should be safe to wait this long, as kernel32.dll should get loaded

before any other DLLs we try to shim at runtime.



For NtCreateSection shim, we modify it to only use stack memory instead

of heap memory. We did not apply the same approach as the

NtMapViewOfSection shim because NtCreateSection is not called for every

DLL load, so the approach to wait for kernel32 would mean the shims have

to depend on each other, though they are not always applied at the same

time.



Modified CheckWin10MsSignedPolicySuccess test so it actually applies the

shims used to load other DLLs on release build. Validated that this test

fails with AppVerifier enabled without these changes and passes with the

changes.



Verified manually with a smoke test that we can run chromium under

page heap, app verifier, and under the conditions from crbug.com/1519187



Also verified manually that sbox integration tests fail under these

conditions without the changes to the shims, and they pass with the

shim changes.



Previously attempted to land here, but reverted due to 1520945:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5214980



Validated that per the previous revert, the change works under

--enable-features=NetworkServiceCodeIntegrity,NetworkServiceSandbox

entry.title: Keep upload request as protos till client
entry.content:
Make it so that records to be uploaded remain protobufs until

`EncryptedReportingClient` level and convert to JSON only there.

The ultimate goal is to allow records to be cached - the cache will

Tested manually on VM and by unit and browser tests.

entry.title: [android/passwords] Check local UPM pref in features_util
entry.content:
Migrate the last kEnablePasswordsAccountStorage production check to

CanCreateAccountStore() and delete the flag. Behavior changes only

behind flag (Before this CL, functions like IsOptedInForAccountStorage()

returned false on Android because the kEnablePasswordsAccountStorage

flag was disabled. Now they continue to return false because they check

the local UPM pref - via CanCreateAccountStore(PrefService*) - and that

is always kOff when the local UPM flag is disabled).



Tests that used override kEnablePasswordsAccountStorage are fixed in a

number of different ways.



1. credential_manager_impl_unittest: CredentialManagerImpl only depends

on the nullness of PasswordManagerClient::GetAccountStore(). The

suite uses a mock client and is already parameterized to test both

cases. So just remove the flag override.

2. password_manager_features_util_unittest: The tests for the touched

logic. Set the UPM pref respectively to kOff/kOn in the

WithoutAccountStorageTest/WithAccountStorageTest suites. The first

is #ifdefed to Android, since it cannot pass on other platforms,

where CanCreateAccountStore() is unconditionally true.

3. form_fetcher_impl_unittest: Same as (1).

4. http_auth_manager_unittest: Same as (1).

5. password_feature_manager_impl_unittest: PasswordFeatureManagerImpl

calls the features_util functions, so this is the same as (2).

6. password_manager_client_helper_unittest: PasswordManagerClientHelper

depends on PasswordFeatureManager and its methods are already mocked

accordingly in each test. Just remove the flag overrides. The test

NoPromptToMoveWithoutFeature is removed because it's essentially a

dupe of NoPromptToMoveForNonOptedInUser, as the flag wasn't directly

checked.

7. password_manager_unittest: PasswordManager uses a bunch of real

objects, including a PasswordFeatureManagerImpl, so same as (5)/(2).

8. password_receiver_service_impl_unittest: PasswordReceiverImpl is

injected with the account store on construction, which can be null or

not, and the parameterized suite already tests both cases. It also

invokes features_util functions, so requires the setup from (2).

9. store_metrics_reporter_unittest: Invokes features_util functions, so

same as (2).

entry.title: [User Education] Address focus issues for WebUI help bubbles.
entry.content:
This addresses several issues around WebUI help bubble focus:

- Anchor element is focused instead of close button for

ShowPromoInPage; this brings behavior in line with most Views help

bubbles, which do not focus the help bubble for toasts. The close

button is still used as a fallback if the anchor cannot be focused.

focus hint, which is now passed to WebUI (it was not previously).

- ShowPromoInPage now focuses the page if it is the active tab.



Accessibility considerations:

- Focusing the anchor rather than the close button does sometimes

cause the anchor to be read by the screenreader instead of the

toast.

- However, since ShowPromoInPage is mostly there to draw visual

attention to the thing that it is anchored to on what could be a

busy page, this doesn't actually hurt the user journey of the

promo bubble.

entry.title: immersive fullscreen: make toolbar style optional
entry.content:
The goal of this CL is to reduce the number of UpdateToolbarVisibility()

calls. We do this in a couple of ways. First the last_used_style_ is now

optional. Immersive fullscreen is enabled before we know what style

should be used. We previously had a default value but this causes churn

when eventually we do get the desired style. This is a factor in

1519600. The optional toolbar style allows us to ignore style updates

when the value is not set.



By reducing the number of calls to UpdateToolbarVisibility() we also

reduce the number of calls to -forceVisibilityRefresh which also

contributes to 1519600 and is the cause of 1519591.

entry.title: Rename FieldClassificationMatchesFillingProduct
entry.content:
Currently, whenever one makes any change to the histogram file, the git

secrets checker will complain that the following line matches a

prohibited pattern:




This forces you to commit with the --no-verify option.



The problem is that the git secret checker regex naively just looks for

key="(40 character string)". By renaming it to

ClassificationMatchesFillingProduct, the check no longer triggers.
